  "market_context": "London session opening, with strong bullish impulse; price had formed equal highs (buy-side liquidity) and equal lows (sell-side liquidity), and a visible Fair Value Gap on the left side of the chart.",
  "key_observation": "The market first swept sell-side liquidity below the equal lows, then rallied to engage buy-side liquidity above the equal highs, while the prior FVG acted as a target for imbalance correction.",
  "analysis_steps": [
    "Step 1: Identified the London session start as a high-liquidity period and marked equal highs (1.09280) as buy-side liquidity and equal lows (1.09160) as sell-side liquidity.",
    "Step 2: Observed a downward move that swept sell-side liquidity below the equal lows, interpreted as a sell-side delivery targeting stop-losses and sell stops.",
    "Step 3: Noted the subsequent upward move toward the buy-side liquidity zone at 1.09280, interpreted as a buy-side delivery engaging buy stops.",
    "Step 4: Identified a Fair Value Gap on the left side (between ~1.09080–1.09160) as an inefficiency created by a strong bullish imbalance, which the market later revisited to restore equilibrium."
  ],
  "outcome": null,
  "lessons": "Markets often sweep liquidity before reversing; FVGs represent inefficiencies that price tends to revisit; institutional delivery aligns with liquidity grabs rather than pure directional bias.",
